How Ancient Stone Trade Routes Shaped European Architecture Forever - The Marble Guide|https://www.usmarble.com/uncategorized/how-ancient-stone-trade-routes-shaped-european-architecture-forever/|the Roman Empire’s systematic quarrying networks to medieval guilds controlling limestone distribution along river  ...    and Greek marble across Mediterranean shipping lanes, medieval overland networks connecting Carrara’s white marble quarries to northern European capitals, and Renaissance-era specialized routes delivering Belgian bluestone and  ...    Medieval cathedral construction relied on extensive stone trade networks along Europe’s major rivers to transport limestone and granite. ### The Rhine and Danube: Europe’s Stone Arteries Europe’s two mighty river systems, the Rhine and Danube, functioned as natural highways for stone commerce from Roman times through the Renaissance. These waterways solved a fundamental challenge: moving massive stone blocks from  ...    The Rhine connected the limestone quarries of the Swiss Alps and sandstone deposits of the Vosges Mountains to  ...    Beyond Istrian stone, Venice operated as a redistribution center for prestigious Italian marbles,
Michelangelo and the marble quarries - Part I - Bazzanti Art Gallery Florence|https://www.galleriabazzanti.it/en/michelangelo-cave-marmo/|Michelangelo reached the marble quarries in Carrara twice, in 1497 and 1503, but Condivi, who wrote the biography  ...    In November 1497 he went there to find marble for the Pietà, a monument contracted by the cardinal of San Dionigi (Jean  ...    eight months. The first contract we have left of this long period in the quarries is dated November 1505 and is related to the transport by sea of 34 cartloads of marble: the cartload is the quantity of marble that a cart with two oxen can tow on the plain, about 850 kg. It was stipulated with two Ligurian of Lavagna boat owners, who in about ten days transported the cargo to Avenza with the boats at the cost of 62 golden ducats, where Michelangelo would have unloaded and transported by sea to Rome at his  ...    the stonemasons Matteo Cuccarello and Guido di Antonio di Biagio who should have brought to the port of Carrara for  ...    withdraw: the marbles for San Pietro, Santa Reparata and San Lorenzo had to be quarried in Pietrasanta.
Carrara marble|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrara_marble|marble". In the Middle Ages, most of the quarries were owned by the Marquis Malaspina who in turn rented them to families of Carrara masters who managed both the extraction and transport of the precious material. Some of  ...    Pietro Buffa, who bought marble on credit from local quarrymen and then resold it on the Venetian market, were able to create a dense commercial network, exporting the marble even to distant locations. Just to cite an example, starting  ...    also taking care of the transport of the material which, by ship, after having circumnavigated Italy, reached the construction site of the monastery after having sailed up the Po and the Ticino by boat. Starting from the 16th century, Genoese stonecutters-merchants also entered this flourishing trade.  ...    The Apuan Alps above Carrara show evidence of at least 650 quarry sites, with about half of them currently abandoned or worked out. The Carr
